<subSubSection id="AA76644F1BB459B281BE7CB4E7BB7B92" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="7908C7D010D6B51FE58EC3935415ADF1" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C1439D2FB94884A661ADCA1E1BEF2685" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="3D8B39C780305CF853CFD6305657C3CB" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="69AA8113DE38CE36232AE9B1DC3A7840" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the similarities with the genera 
<taxonomicName id="EFB0F710C8D8E0BD45E5B782C206376F" authorityName="Dognin" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Gaujonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujonia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A0C4C8A47DE1EF276DA8B3BC3A9C734A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E64657EFAE7BE8F538D2311FEAE880B3" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1856" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Lichnoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lichnoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C0660C05E5277DBD8084918E1C997790" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Lichnoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FCAC0254AD4B01F9B4DB58424BE425FA" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="included species">
<paragraph id="E6616C1049D16092A807A11C58AB60F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Included species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3C097A03D313822A038D3D5949093395" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="D66E79AA296B08042C99987D8ED0E11F" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="67560525613F13676D73D5EFD9015DE3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is monotypic, the only species is 
<taxonomicName id="4D81D264636F59A7B04AF1798D471443" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera amsa" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amsa">
<emphasis id="24AAF22B3F219A48E2C4882A6556EC76" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera amsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., which was misidentified as a 
<taxonomicName id="C25C60EBA7790CD6D6279586F7276A55" authorityName="Dognin" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Gaujonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujonia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F8F2D67760BB1DB688DA710E238DE2AC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species; however, morphological and molecular analyses resulted in recognizing a new genus that is positioned close to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="36A7CB2048BB88386F9C4F44E3121472" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Millerana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Millerana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8A87F1EA3C1C514F4C3CEE8E26657B03" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Millerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F1B3CAEDBA91813E029ADB0B26811803" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Maximum likelihood tree showing relationships between the Gaujonia genus group and the rest of the other jaguar moth genera based on the cytochrome c oxidase I gene (COI) marker. Nodes with black circles represent high support (UFBoot ≥ 95 and SH-aLRT ≥ 80). Nodes with gray circles represent low support (UFBoot &lt;95 and SH-aLRT &lt;80). Black branches constitute the outgroups." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.985.51622.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471601" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A6E24E557B657C635C3AE603962663CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A0643AFAEBDA2C6BE33786D970324C04" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0AABBB9F23E06E94074BD9DE6CAE929E" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="72F64243CFBE8479970D8D3056343A61" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BEF09F8D8E7373CE902C996852E25003" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from two well-preserved male specimens and it has a close relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="F1939478E815F076556DE63EE36DC302" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Millerana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Millerana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5B86476B6C2ECF639713198CD2675B9C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Millerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, not only genetically, but also by distinct morphological characters. Nevertheless, the wing pattern is more defined in 
<taxonomicName id="19052214A7FF2A12844940170BE36D8F" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Millerana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Millerana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D05755F43F9AAE672621EB95EB8DA320" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Millerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than in 
<taxonomicName id="00368963B54EACEA5A1D14360C41A714" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F8EDF7F70D146A0CAB2915E54DB83CAC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has a blurry pattern that is difficult to discern. In addition, the thorax is marbled with black, gray, brown, and sulfur-yellow scales, differing from species of 
<taxonomicName id="63277EB2B6710B6D342FBC896BDEA46E" authorityName="Dognin" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Gaujonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujonia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C2C3A1450F2CA16A29A929D279BE32C2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which have the black spots and patches well defined on the thorax. 
<taxonomicName id="ACA65423795BDD5410CA3764561D5393" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C745E1EF6AD607E5E2E51814C96BAE33" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not have a V-shaped mark at the base of CuA2. The most important feature to differentiate 
<taxonomicName id="F089F67CD99650AA358B369E1EC53698" authority="Martinez, 2020" authorityName="Martinez" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Gaujoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CCE7D824A88095324A798C549490E438" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="A86E2F7CC5F7739D2E3B052D230DA495" authorityName="Dognin" authorityYear="1891" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Gaujonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gaujonia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9E73837B51B75B86A50DD3885891171E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Gaujonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the presence of small clasper on the valva, similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="BD49F181D8AF92A34CC8B5FF2F9345C0" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1856" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Lichnoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lichnoptera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="982609B31D4E25A4630E901235EC6920" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Lichnoptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="92684042364B13CCD590B5C91D356A4A" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph id="7848DB911EA5839FA74EEDFE2173B15B" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6DC1764A41DCDB700D54E8B8B8ADAB6D" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Forewing and hindwing dark sulfur-yellow with an inconspicuous pattern, only reniform spot visible. Hindwing hyaline with scales only on margins. Antenna filiform, with a short brownish orange haustellum; eye hairy with short interfacial setae. Male genitalia simple in male with small triangular clasper; small, curved uncus; aedeagus shorter than vesica; vesica with small spines in middle. Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
